{{orphan|date=September 2017}}
The [[Forms of government|Government]] of United [[Republic]] of [[Tanzania]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tanzania.go.tz|title=United Republic of Tanzania, Government portal|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> has enacted four Acts concerning with the control of freedom and regulation of media in the [[country]]. These are The [[Cybercrimes Act in Tanzania|Cybercrimes Act, 2015]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parliament.go.tz/polis/uploads/bills/acts/1452061463-ActNo-14-2015-Book-11-20.pdf|title=Cybercrime Act, 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>, The [[Statistics]] Act, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parliament.go.tz/polis/uploads/bills/acts/1452062087-ActNo-9-2015-Book-1-10.pdf|title=The Statistic Act, 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>, The Media Services Act, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parliament.go.tz/polis/uploads/bills/1474021216-A%20BILL%20-%20%20%20THE%20MEDIA%20SERVICES%20ACT,%202016.pdf|title=The Media Service Act, 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>, and The Access to [[Information]] Act, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twaweza.org/uploads/files/THE%20ACCESS%20TO%20INFORMATION%20ACT.pdf|title=The Access to Information Act 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>. The Government of the Republic of Tanzania on one side claims that the four Acts were highly needed to facilitate access to information and control the media sector. [[Politics|Political]] analysts, [[Activism|activists]] and normal people on the other side criticized that the Acts will pessimistically affect the [[Liberty|freedom]] of media and eventually the freedom of speech of [[Citizenship|citizens]]. The Acts give the [[Minister without portfolio|Minister]] responsible for information the power to ban any media which may seems to report, publish, print or broadcast information contrary to the code of conducts or threaten peace in the state.
== Brief history == The Media Services Act, 2016, was enacted in 2016 by the [[parliament]] of the united republic of Tanzania<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.go.tz/|title=The Parliament Of United Republic Of Tanzania|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> on 5 November 2016 and signed by [[President]] [[John Pombe Magufuli]] just two weeks later. The Act replaced the then restrictive [[Newspaper]] Act of 1976. The Expectation to many people was that, the Act would to become an updated media law that will obey to international conventions like United Nation Declaration of [[Human rights]] (UNDHR), [[East African Community Treaty]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eac.int/sites/default/files/docs/treaty_eac_amended-2006_1999.pdf|title=The Treaty for the Establishment of the East African Community|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> and others on citizen liberty to access information but unexpectedly the Acts seems to many as depriving of civil constitutional<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.judiciary.go.tz/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/constitution.pdf|title=THE UNITED REPUBLIC, POLITICAL PARTIES, THE PEOPLE AND THE POLICY OF SOCIALISM AND SELF RELIANCE|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> rights like freedom of expression and freedom of getting information.
== Reaction from press == The Media Council of Tanzania (MCT), Legal and Human Right Centre<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.humanrights.or.tz/|title=The Legal and Human Rights Centre|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> (LHRC), and Tanzania Human Rights Defenders Coalition<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.achpr.org/files/tanzania_hrd_coaliton_statement.pdf|title=African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> (THRDC) on 11th of January 2017 filed a petition at the East African Court of Justice<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eacj.org/|title=Welcome to the East African Court of Justice|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> (EACJ) to challenge the newly passed Media Service Act, 2016. The team of lawyers from MCT, LHRC and THRDC are challenging sections of the Media Services Act, 2016 which appeared to deprive the civil liberties to access and getting information. According to the constitution of Tanzania Article 18 (a), (b), (c) and (d) Some deprived constitutional civil rights by the Media service Acts are; * Freedom of opinion and expression ideas * Right to seek, receive and, or disseminate information regardless of national boundaries; * Freedom to communicate and a freedom with protection from interference * Right to be informed at all times of various important events of life and activities of the people and also of issues of importance to the society
